07574nam a22011415i 9783110641325DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106413257 a10.1515/97831106413252doi  a(DE-B1597)507676  a(OCoLC)1253314129  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090102bisacsh00aComparison and Gradation in Indo-European /ced. by Wolfgang Hock, Götz Keydana, Paul Widmer. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VIII, 597 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Mouton Handbooks of Indo-European Typology [MHIET] ,x2511-7742 ;v100tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tTable of Contents -- t1 Comparison and Gradation in Indo- European: Introduction and Overview -- t2 Anatolian -- t3 Classical Armenian -- t4 Old Albanian -- t5 Ancient Languages of the Balkans -- t6 Baltic -- t7 Old Church Slavonic -- t8 Brittonic -- t9 Continental Celtic -- t10 Goidelic -- t11 Old Nordic -- t12 West Germanic -- t13 Ancient Greek -- t14 Old Indo-Aryan -- t15 Old Iranian -- t16 Latin -- t17 Sabellian -- t18 Tocharian -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe ability to compare is fundamental to human cognition. Expressing various types of comparison is thus essential to any language. The present volume presents detailed grammatical descriptions of how comparison and gradation are expressed in ancient Indo-European languages. The detailed chapters devoted to the individual languages go far beyond standard handbook knowledge. Each chapter is structured the same way to facilitate cross-reference and (typological) comparison. The data are presented in a top-down fashion and in a format easily accessible to the linguistic community.The topics covered are similatives, equatives, comparatives, superlatives, elatives, and excessives. Each type of comparison is illustrated with glossed examples of all its attested grammatical realizations.The book is an indispensable tool for typologists, historical linguists, and students of the syntax and morphosyntax of comparison.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aHistorische Linguistik. 4aIndo-Europäisch. 4aTypologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Historical & Comparative.2bisacsh  aIndo-European, Typology, Gradation, Comparison.1 aAckermann, Katsiaryna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupraz, Emmanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnger, Hans-Olav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFellner, Hannes A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGenesin, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffith, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHock, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHock, Wolfgang, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHöder, Steffen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIttzés, Máté, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJäger, Agnes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeydana, Götz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeydana, Götz, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKreij, Nina de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKulikov, Leonid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKölligan, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalzahn, Melanie